:::summary
Cleopatra VII (69–30 BC) was the last active ruler of the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt — a brilliant, multilingual queen whose alliances with Julius Caesar and Mark Antony shaped the final decades of the Roman Republic. More than a romantic figure, Cleopatra was a capable stateswoman who fought fiercely to preserve Egyptian sovereignty against the rising tide of Roman power.
:::

